240. ex noto fictum. Is Horace still speaking of the diction of a Satyric drama? So Acr.‚ followed by Orelli and other editors, on the ground that otherwise he is made to pass from dic- tion to plot and back again to diction in v. 244. But ‘ fingere carmen ex ' is most naturally interpreted of the plot, and if these verses really referred to the dic- tion, we should have in v. 244 some conjunction to indicate that the precept there given was a limitation of what preceded. That passage stands, as this one does, without a conjunction, be- cause they are both independent of the lines before them. Ritter seems rightly to indicate what differences vv. 244 f. from vv. 225—239. See on v. 244. The difficulty of connection has seemed so great to some editors that they have thought vv. 240—243 to be out of their place. Ribbeck omits them3 but they are in Horace’s best style.
